      },
      "date": "2017-08-30 05:51:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIs this really the best solution? Currently Ubuntu is broken in general. For example I see the following when I run make and then make debs:\n\nchecking whether mpitests can be built... no\nchecking whether to build Linux kernel modules... yes (linux-gnu)\nfind: '/usr/src/kernels/': No such file or directory\nchecking for Linux sources... readlink: missing operand\nTry 'readlink --help' for more information.\n\nchecking for ... no\nconfigure: error: Kernel source  could not be found.\ndebian/rules:328: recipe for target 'kdist_config' failed\nmake[2]: *** [kdist_config] Error 1\nmake[2]: Leaving directory '/usr/src/lustre-2.10.52/debian/tmp/modules-deb/usr_src/modules/lustre'\n/usr/src/lustre-2.10.52/debian/tmp/modules-deb/usr_share_modass/include/common-rules.make:56: recipe for target 'kdist_build' failed\nmake[1]: *** [kdist_build] Error 2\n\nThis is due to the landing of LU-9775. So far the track record for Ubuntu support have been really poor. Just look at LU-9564. Also the version of the compact file used by lustre for packaging is considered not to be supported any more.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
